{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15280"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.58,0.06,0.1,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7971"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6970"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45196"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute pancreatitis is a condition characterised by rapid inflammation of the pancreas. The two main aetiological factors are gallstones and alcohol consumption. The condition leads to the release of pancreatic enzymes that begin to digest the pancreas itself and surrounding tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is NOT typically seen on histological examination of acute pancreatitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fat necrosis","Fibrosis","Ghost outlines of fat cells","Haemorrhage","Calcium soap deposits"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute pancreatitis, the release of pancreatic enzymes (particularly lipase) leads to autodigestion of pancreatic and peripancreatic tissues. This results in several characteristic histological findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFat necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a hallmark feature of acute pancreatitis, caused by the action of pancreatic lipase on adipose tissue. This enzymatic destruction of fat is distinct from other forms of necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of chronic pancreatitis, where repeated episodes of inflammation lead to replacement of pancreatic parenchyma with fibrous tissue. It is not a feature of acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhost outlines of fat cells\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in areas of fat necrosis, where the cell membranes remain visible but the cellular contents have been destroyed by enzymatic digestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly observed in acute pancreatitis, particularly in severe cases, due to destruction of blood vessels by proteolytic enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium soap deposits\u003C/strong\u003E result from saponification, where liberated fatty acids from fat necrosis combine with calcium ions to form insoluble calcium soaps, appearing as basophilic deposits on histology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pancreatitis is characterised by enzymatic fat necrosis, haemorrhage, and acute inflammation.","Fat necrosis in acute pancreatitis shows ghost outlines of fat cells and calcium soap formation (saponification).","Fibrosis is a feature of chronic pancreatitis, not acute pancreatitis."],"references":["Szatmary P, Grammatikopoulos T, Cai W, Huang W, Mukherjee R, Halloran C, Beyer G, Sutton R. Acute Pancreatitis: Diagnosis and Treatment. Drugs. 2022 Aug;82(12):1251-1276. doi: 10.1007/s40265-022-01766-4. Epub 2022 Sep 8. PMID: 36074322; PMCID: PMC9454414.","Mederos MA, Reber HA, Girgis MD. Acute Pancreatitis: A Review. JAMA. 2021 Jan 26;325(4):382-390. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.20317. Erratum in: JAMA. 2021 Jun 15;325(23):2405. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.5789. PMID: 33496779.","Kumar  Vinay  MBBS  MD  FRCPath,Abbas  Abul K.  MBBS,Aster  Jon C.  MD  PhD,Deyrup  Andrea T.  MD  PhD,Das  Abhijit  MD, 15 - Pancreas, Robbins \u0026 Kumar Basic Pathology (Eleventh Edition), edited by Kumar  Vinay  MBBS  MD  FRCPath,Abbas  Abul K.  MBBS,Aster  Jon C.  MD  PhD,Deyrup  Andrea T.  MD  PhD,Das  Abhijit  MD, 2023, Pages 572-581, ISBN 978-0-323-79018-5, http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-323-79018-5.00015-1.\n (https://www.clinicalkey.com/student/content/book/3-s2.0-B9780323790185000151)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93305"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-10T13:21:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-10T13:22:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7971"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t